{"cursor":"6504","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox music genre |name=Novelty songs |color=|bgcolor=\n|stylistic_origins=Popular music |cultural_origins =1910s United States\n|instruments =Guitar, Bass, drums, often also keyboards |popularity = Grammy\ncategory since 1959\n|derivatives=|subgenrelist=|subgenres=|fusiongenres=|regional_scenes=\n|other_topics=Parody music - Comedy rock }}\n\nA 'novelty song' is a comical or nonsensical song, performed principally for its\ncomical effect. Humorous songs, or those containing humorous elements, are not\nnecessarily novelty songs. The term arose in Tin Pan Alley to describe one of\nthe major divisions of popular music. The other two divisions were ballads and\ndance music. Hamm, Irving Berlin Early Songs, p. xxxiv: \"The text of a\nnovelty song sketches a vignette or a brief story of an amusing or provocative\nnature. ... noted for portraying characters of specific ethnicity or those\nfinding themselves in certain comic or melodramatic situations, ...\"\nNovelty songs achieved great popularity during the 1920s and 1930s. Axford,\nSong Sheets to Software, p. 20: \"As sentimental songs were the mainstay of Tin\nPan Alley, novelty and comical songs helped to break the monotony, developing in\nthe twenties and thirties as signs of the times.\" Tawa, Supremely\nAmerican, p. 55: \"... in the 1920s, novelty songs offset the intensely serious\nand lachrymose ballads. nonsensical novelty songs, reproducing the irrational\nand meaningless side of the twenties, made frequent appearances.\"\n\nNovelty songs are often a parody or humor song, and may apply to a current event\nsuch as a holiday or a fad such as a dance. Many use unusual lyrics, subjects,\nsounds, or instrumentation, and may not even be musical. \"They're Coming to Take\nMe Away, Ha-Haaa!\" has little music and is set to a rhythm tapped out on a snare\ndrum and tambourine. One novelty song, a remix of \"Axel F\" by Crazy Frog,\nstarted as a mobile phone ringtone.\n","linknr":159,"url":"Novelty_songs","recorded":1375066400,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Novelty_song&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Novelty_song&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Novelty_song","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Novelty_songs&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Popular_music","/wiki/Guitar","/wiki/Bass_guitar","/wiki/Drum_kit","/wiki/Keyboard_instrument","/wiki/Parody_music","/wiki/Comedy_rock","/wiki/Song","/wiki/Comedy","/wiki/Tin_Pan_Alley","/wiki/Popular_music","/wiki/Ballad_(music)","/wiki/Dance_music","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Parody","/wiki/Novelty_and_fad_dances","/wiki/They%27re_Coming_to_Take_Me_Away,_Ha-Haaa!","/wiki/Snare_drum","/wiki/Tambourine","/wiki/Axel_F","/wiki/Crazy_Frog","/wiki/Ringtone","/w/index.php?title=Novelty_song&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Tin_Pan_Alley","/wiki/K-K-K-Katy","/wiki/Yes!_We_Have_No_Bananas","/wiki/Oh_By_Jingo!","/wiki/Nagasaki_(song)","/wiki/Spike_Jones#Der_Fuehrer.27s_Face","/wiki/(How_Much_Is)_That_Doggie_in_the_Window%3F","/wiki/Dickie_Goodman","http://www.billboard.com/artist/300899/dickie+goodman/biography","/wiki/The_Flying_Saucer_(song)","/wiki/Sampling_(music)","/wiki/Yakety_Yak","/wiki/Hot_100_number-one_